Dr. Theobald records many instances of parallel phrases in Bacon and Shakespeare, and in one or two cases he qualifies them with remarks to the effect that such phrases are sometimes to be met with in other writers of the time. Consequendy, we may assume that the absence of qualifying remarks is an indication that the phrases are new and of Bacon's coinage.

Starting holes.—This phrase is said to be a curious one, and a passage in 1 Hem-y IV. which contains it is quoted. Of course, Bacon uses it.

Two instances at least occur in Jonson: one in The Case is Altered‚ and the other in the Discoverie53 De Bonis et Malis. It is a very common expression, and Peele used it in the earliest known draft of his Edward L, but struck it out when revising his play, perhaps because it had been battered about so much by others. See Dyce's Pede, p. 415, col. 1. Greene often uses it, and it occurs in Gascoigne’s Voyage into Helland, 1572.
